      {
        "paragraph_index": 1,
        "text": "### Why?\n\nNIST SRD-46 (the **NIST Critically Selected Stability Constants of Metal Complexes** database) is specifically focused on **aqueous-phase** equilibrium data. It was designed to compile and critically evaluate metal–ligand stability constants determined in aqueous solution. Measurements in exotic media such as supercritical CO₂, ionic liquids, or organic solvents fall outside its scope.\n\nIf you need stability data in supercritical CO₂, you might consider:\n- **Primary literature** searches (e.g., via SciFinder or Web of Science) — some studies have examined metal–chelate complexes in scCO₂ for applications like supercritical fluid extraction.\n- **IUPAC Stability Constants Database (SC-Database)** — which has broader solvent coverage in some areas.\n\n*Source: NIST SRD-46*",
